From the storage tanks, ammonia vapor is delivered by tank pressure to each combustion turbine unit via pipeline. The regulated ammonia vapor supply from the storage tank is mixed with air provided by air blowers on the ammonia dilution skid next to each combustion turbine. The ammonia/air mixture is forwarded to the ammonia injection grid located in the combustion turbine's hot gas exhaust stream upstream of the catalyst module in the Heat Recovery Steam Generator (NOx reduction process).

3. Accidental release prevention program:

The facility's accidental release prevention program is modeled after and in compliance with federal and State programs for managing hazardous chemical processes. It meets the requirements of Cal-OSHA's Process Safety Management standard, EPA's Chemical Accident Prevention Provisions, and the California Accidental Release Prevention Program (CalARP).

Specific elements of the program include: Employee Participation, Process Safety Information, Process Hazard Analysis, Operating Procedures, Training, Contractor Safety, Contractor and Visitor Orientation, Pre-Job Startup Review, Mechanical Integrity, Code of Safe Practices, Management of Change, Incident Investigation, Emergency Planning and Response, and Compliance Audits.

Specific accident prevention steps include the following programs, procedures, and practices:
o Initial and annual training in PSM;
o Integrity testing and inspection of process equipment/piping;
o Employee participation in the MOC process and PHA;
o Unrestricted access to process safety information by employees and contrac

tors;
o Operator training program which includes initial, on the job training, and refresher training and demonstration of competency;
o Hot Work Permit procedure;
o Confined Space Entry procedure;
o Lockout/Tagout/Try Procedure;
o Code of Safe Work Practices;
o Respiratory Protection Program
o HAZCOM program;
o Procedure for opening process equipment and piping;
o Controlled/limited access to facility and process areas;
o Periodic training on selected health, safety, and environmental topics;
o Emergency Action & Response Plan for all plant personnel;  
o Contractor Safety Selection and Monitoring Policy.

4. The five-year accident history:

PEF has had no reportable accidents or incidences that resulted in injury, environmental damage, or off-site impact related to the ammonia system/process.

5. The emergency response program:

The emergency response program/plan is written and posted in each office of the Administration Building and in a dedicated binder located in Control Room. The plan describes the evacuation procedures, the emergency actions to take, individual responsibilities during an emergency, and the appropriate notifications and contacts to make for specific types of emergency events.  Plant evacuations are initiated by activating an audible signal, and communications through employee radios. The plan is reviewed and coordinated with the Kern County Fire Department on a periodic basis.

Emergency Action and Response training is conducted at least annually with all PEF employees. Training includes the specific responsibilities and duties that each PEF employee should take in the event of an emergency. Training will also include coordination, involvement and emergency drill exercises with local emergency responder (Kern County Fire Department and Hazardous Materials Division, and the Hazardous Material Contractor selected by PEF.

Maintenance and testing of the emergency equipment is scheduled in the facility's computerized maintenance management system
